<br>
What I propose is a raid set up with a puller (Monk), a tagger (anyone that can survive a tag), and then 2-4 (!) &quot;Main Tanks&quot;, each with a healer assigned to keeping them alive.  The puller goes to grab a mob as usual, the tagger brings it back to the raid party, and the first main tank engages.  The monk then rushes out for another, and the process continues until the raid party is engaging 2-4 mobs simultaneously.  The mobs are &quot;bunched&quot; together back at the raid party and can even be rooted in place for initial placement and aggro management.<br>
<br>
The great benefit to this is that in some raids zones adds always happen regardless, and while mezzing / Charming adds is somewhat effective, some mobs are simply immune to these effects and hard to pull single anyways.  Splitting Tanks on the &quot;adds&quot; and having all AE / Rain spell capable casters burn them down is a solution that is not only effective, but highly efficient.<br>
<br>
To illustrate the efficiency of this strategy here are some facts-<br>
<br>
My typical single target nuke, Draught of Ice, costs 215 mana to do 731 damage, 3.4 damage per point of mana spent.  Tears of Prexus, my typical AE rain spell, costs 437 mana and on 2 targets would land 2 waves of 690 damage per wave, 6.3 damage per mana point spent.  This is an 85% INCREASE in damage and mana efficiency for controlling just a single additional mob and having it placed in relatively close proximity to the first so that they are both in the Area of Effect of the spell.<br>
<br>
If 3 or even 4 (!) mobs are pulled and &quot;bunched&quot;, I can use Pillar of Flame; 952 damage to all targets for 364 mana.  7.9 dmg per point of mana for three targets, 10.5 damage per mana point spent on 4 targets.<br>
<br>
Many classes have at least one AE spell available, and many have multiple.  Aggro control is actually easier for melee support classes (rogues, etc), or those caster classes that use single target spells in this circumstance, as they have more targets they can switch between.  Shaman even have an AE slow spell if I am not mistaken.<br>
<br>
What I plan to do is ATTEMPT a planned raid on umbral with this strategy in mind, for the purposes of perfecting the technique and of course having a great time.  So long as groups are balanced and pulling goes well we can EASILLY see our caster's impact DOUBLED.  This is turn will prepare us for the new and exciting content Verant is implementing such as the different Ring Quests (Ring of Fire, new Cazic Thule Ring, etc., etc.).<br>
<br>
Any comments or suggestions are welcome, I really think with the right coordination and communication The Federation can incorporate a variety of strategies which will ultimately make us a more powerful raiding force. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000060><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub70.ezboard.com/ufilumtil.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Filumtil</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Federation Admin</span><br>  Posts: 106<br> <font color=#70DB93>(6/13/02 4:57:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub70.ezboard.com/ffederationofpovarfrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=99.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.camelot.de/~ekraemer/filumtil3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Multiple mob pulling strategy</span><hr size=1> I think this is a good idea, and would *really* like to be part of the group that tries this.<br>
<br>
Maybe there would, for a first try, another good place instead of Umbral? Umbral has very high-level mobs, which have a good chance of resisting (not sure about you wizards, but some of them sure have a good MR if I remember right).<br>
<br>
As you say, I think almost every caster class will find some way to fight different/with increased effectiveness in such a situation, given time. For example, AE stuns, while not much use in a single-mob, many-people-fight, may be very usefull here, since they take away the damage of the mobs for one round, at least, if not chain stunning. For the usual hitters in the 100-200's, that would, for 4 mobs, be 400-800 damage NOT done by the mobs, per cast. Sounds not too bad, not taking crits/doubles/quads in account.<br>
