<br>
Scenario: 4 Main Tanks, 1 Rogue.<br>
<br>
- Pulls start.<br>
- After a while, all 4 MTs have a mob.<br>
- Rogue waits a little.<br>
- Rogue attacks the 1st mob, doing full damage, until he has the agro.<br>
- Rogue stops attacking immediately and moves to second mob.<br>
- By this time, the 2nd MT has a large agro, and the rogue will be able to hit the 2nd mob a long while before agroing. The 1st MT will get the 1st mob back in no time, since the Rogue switched target immediately after getting agro.<br>
<br>
This continues until the 4th mob is attacked by the rogue, and cycles back to the 1st mob.<br>
<br>
This way, the rogue can ALWAYS do FULL damage during the WHOLE time; he never has to stop fighting or backstabbing. After all, we can't always hope to have 4 Main Tanks on Gotrik's agro level <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  , so this strategy would have to been used anyway, by the rogues at least.<br>
<br>
Same goes, of course, for any other melee class with high damage output, &quot;rogue&quot; was just used as an example.<br>
<br>
It also works for all casters that only have single target spells... like Necros with their dots... cast one dot on each of the mob, then another dot on each of the mobs... by the time the 2nd dot hits the 1st mob, the MT safely has the agro (bad example since the fights won't last long <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ).<br>
<br>
