Feppsi <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000080><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub70.ezboard.com/uravilicuslolf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ravilicus LoLF</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Soldier of the Federation</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#70DB93>(6/14/02 8:48:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub70.ezboard.com/ffederationofpovarfrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=99.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Multiple mob pulling strategy</span><hr size=1> The average lifespan of a mob in PoG isn't long enough to kill a tank generally speaking so long as that tank has a healer assigned to it, especially when that mob is getting hit by a dozen caster's AE blasts.<br>
<br>
In Umbral, this is different and bring up a valid point.  The mobs have hella ton of hit points can really can tear through a tank without too much difficulty.  For places like Umbral i would certainly suggest trying to just do Duo-pulls with a primary and secondary tank, basically an intentional split.<br>
<br>
In places like PoG and Fear where pullers go pretty far out and often grab unmezzable adds, the only change in behavior besides the spliting we normally do ANYWAYS is that the tanks try to position the mobs close together so they can be AE-d.<br>
<br>
It isn't as dramatic a change in playstyle as it seems when you take it all in, but it certainly can be used to extreme effectiveness when there are MANY mobs that need killing, and sufficient tank to do the crowd control instead of the enchanters.<br>
<br>
A nice thing about this is that since the enchanters aren't frantically trying to keep the &quot;adds&quot; mezzed, they can have their charm spells prepared to use any SINGLE add as a pet that they can use against the current target(s).<br>
<br>
